        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer518246417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4231948736499391337">Heisenberg&apos;s Physics and Philosophy. I found it interesting to read though I have only layman knowledge about quantum mechanics and its implications. But, I never felt bored anytime even with my limited understanding of the subject. The book goes into details about the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics, its criticisms and so on. But, what I found deeply engrossing is the discussion on the reality and limitation of language in expressing the quantum mechanics concepts. The words whic</span>
  <span id="freeText4231948736499391337" style="display:none">Heisenberg's Physics and Philosophy. I found it interesting to read though I have only layman knowledge about quantum mechanics and its implications. But, I never felt bored anytime even with my limited understanding of the subject. The book goes into details about the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics, its criticisms and so on. But, what I found deeply engrossing is the discussion on the reality and limitation of language in expressing the quantum mechanics concepts. The words which we commonly use from a classical sense seems to lose its meaning in the quantum world. <br /><br />"In classical logic, it is assumed that, if a statement has any meaning at all, either the statement or the negation of the statement must be correct. Of 'here is a table' or 'here is not a table' either the first or second one must be correct. 'Tertium non datur', a third possibility does not exist. It may be that we do not know whether a statement or its negation is correct, but in 'reality' one of the two is correct.<br />In quantum theory this law 'tertium non datur' is to be modified."<br /><br />The only equation which is used in this book is the weird "2 x 2 =5". It was quite surprising to me that a mathematically rich subject like quantum mechanics can be discussed in ~150 pages without any mathematics!<br /><br />A thought-provoking book. Must read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4231948736499391337" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


